  <h2>What PDRN actually is</h2>
  <p>
    PDRN stands for <strong>polydeoxyribonucleotide</strong> — short fragments
    of DNA, typically ranging from 50 to 1,500 kilodaltons in molecular weight.
    The DNA is extracted from salmon sperm (specifically <em>Oncorhynchus
    keta</em>, chum salmon) and then purified to remove all proteins. What's
    left is a biocompatible chain of nucleotides that's structurally similar to
    human DNA.
  </p>
  <p>
    "Salmon DNA skincare" sounds like a marketing gimmick. It isn't. PDRN has
    been used in medical settings since the early 2000s — as an injectable
    treatment for wound healing, tissue regeneration, and post-procedure
    recovery. Korean dermatology clinics have offered PDRN injections (sometimes
    called "salmon injections") for over a decade. The move to topical skincare
    products started around 2024, and by 2026 it's the dominant ingredient
    trend in K-beauty.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>
    PDRN's primary mechanism is through the <strong>A2A adenosine receptor
    pathway</strong>. When PDRN fragments interact with A2A purinergic
    receptors on your skin cells, they trigger a cascade that:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Stimulates fibroblasts</strong> — the cells responsible for
      producing collagen and elastin. Research suggests PDRN can increase
      collagen synthesis by 25–35% over 8–12 weeks.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Reduces inflammation</strong> — by modulating the A2A pathway,
      PDRN suppresses pro-inflammatory cytokines. This is why it was originally
      used for wound healing.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Promotes cell turnover</strong> — PDRN provides raw nucleotide
      building blocks that cells can use for repair and proliferation, which
      supports faster skin renewal.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    One clinical study on skin graft patients found that PDRN-treated wounds
    fully healed in 12.5 days compared to 24.5 days in the control group.
    That's real, measurable tissue regeneration — not a before-and-after photo
    with different lighting.
  </p>

  <h2>The honest take: injectable vs. topical</h2>
  <p>
    Here's what most PDRN marketing won't tell you: <strong>most of the
    impressive clinical data is for injectable PDRN</strong>, not topical serums.
  </p>
  <p>
    When injected directly into the dermis, PDRN bypasses the skin barrier
    entirely and reaches fibroblasts at full concentration. The 25–35% collagen
    increase, the wound healing acceleration, the anti-aging effects — that
    evidence comes from needles, not bottles.
  </p>
  <p>
    Topical PDRN faces a fundamental challenge: <strong>it's a large
    molecule</strong>. DNA fragments don't penetrate the stratum corneum as
    easily as smaller actives like retinol, niacinamide, or vitamin C. This
    doesn't mean topical PDRN does nothing — early research shows it can
    improve hydration and skin barrier function — but the large-scale anti-aging
    evidence for topical application isn't on par with established actives yet.
  </p>
  <p>
    Think of it this way: retinol has 50+ years of topical studies behind it.
    PDRN has about 5 years of topical research and 20+ years of injectable data.
    It's promising, not proven at the same level.
  </p>

  <h2>Who it's actually good for</h2>
  <p>
    Based on the current science, topical PDRN makes the most sense for:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Compromised or sensitised skin</strong> — if your barrier is
      damaged from over-exfoliation, retinol irritation, or post-procedure
      recovery, PDRN's anti-inflammatory and regenerative properties are well
      suited. This is closest to the original clinical use case.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Dehydrated skin that needs repair</strong> — the hydration and
      barrier-strengthening benefits of topical PDRN are the best-supported
      topical claims.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Redness and uneven tone</strong> — PDRN's anti-inflammatory
      action helps with redness, post-acne marks, and hyperpigmentation
      recovery.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>K-beauty enthusiasts who want the next edge</strong> — if you're
      already layering essences, serums, and SPF, a PDRN serum slots in
      naturally and the ingredient profile is genuinely interesting.
    </li>
  </ul>

