  <h2>How to use PDRN in your routine</h2>
  <p>
    PDRN serums are water-based and lightweight, so they go in the same step as
    any other serum — after cleansing and toning, before moisturiser and
    sunscreen.
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Cleanse</strong> — double cleanse if you're wearing SPF or makeup</li>
    <li><strong>Tone</strong> — optional (or use a PDRN toner like the Medicube Milky Toner to double up)</li>
    <li><strong>PDRN serum</strong> — 2–3 drops, pat gently into damp skin</li>
    <li><strong>Moisturise</strong> — seal everything in</li>
    <li><strong>Sunscreen</strong> — always, every morning</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    PDRN pairs well with niacinamide, hyaluronic acid, and peptides. It's
    generally safe to use alongside retinol, but if your skin is already
    sensitised from retinol, PDRN's barrier-repair properties make it a good
    alternative on your "off nights."
  </p>

  <h2>PDRN vs. other trending ingredients</h2>
  <p>
    The 2026 K-beauty ingredient landscape also includes <strong>exosomes</strong>
    and <strong>snail mucin</strong> as top contenders. Here's how PDRN
    compares:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>PDRN vs. exosomes</strong> — both are regenerative, but exosomes
      are cell-derived vesicles that carry growth factors, while PDRN is pure
      DNA fragments. Exosome products are typically more expensive and even
      newer to topical skincare. PDRN has more clinical history.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>PDRN vs. snail mucin</strong> — snail mucin is primarily a
      hydrator and soother (glycoproteins, hyaluronic acid). PDRN targets a
      different mechanism entirely (cell signalling via A2A receptors). They're
      complementary, not competitors — you can use both.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>PDRN vs. retinol</strong> — retinol is still the gold standard
      for proven topical anti-aging. PDRN is gentler and works through a
      completely different pathway. If retinol irritates your skin, PDRN is a
      reasonable alternative. If you tolerate retinol well, PDRN adds to your
      routine rather than replacing it.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    PDRN is a genuinely interesting ingredient with real science behind it —
    not another hyped-up plant extract. The injectable form has strong clinical
    evidence for tissue regeneration and collagen production. The topical form
    is promising for hydration, barrier repair, and anti-inflammatory benefits,
    but it's not yet at the evidence level of retinol or vitamin C for
    anti-aging specifically.
  </p>
  <p>
